Semilarski v. Prosecutor’s Office: the cassation of the former Deputy Mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to consider Semilarski’s claim, but in April his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, since its resolution was not within the competence of the administrative court.
The court's decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“These issues should be regulated by the prosecutor’s office and the district court,” the Tartu Courts spokeswoman Anette Creutzmann told ERR earlier.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the state will have to say its word.
According to defense attorney Semilarski, Oliver Nees’s juror, his client had been unreasonably suspected of bribery for about two years.
He now demands from the prosecutor’s office to refute the false allegations against him and compensate him for the moral damages.
The reason for filing a complaint to the court were the statements of the prosecutor in special cases of the Lyuna district prosecutor Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with the other Vice Mayor of Tartu, Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“When I was arrested, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu – one of the most influential bodies of local self-government – were corrupt.
These public suspicions that hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor's office does not want to say anything about it," Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Neas, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The allegation of bribery and bribery turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, state representatives should be careful in choosing the words so that suspects are not represented as criminals before the sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is obliged to do so by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not observed in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Nees said.
“The public perception of Semilarski as a serious offender and briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being clarified is unacceptable, contrary to the presumption of innocence and unfair to the applicant,” the lawyer added.
According to rus.err.ee, the former Vice Mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be brought to justice on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him was partially closed in July.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, between 2015 and 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated in the meetings of the city administration more than thirty times in making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarsky actively communicated on a personal level during non-working hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to withdraw from participation in decision-making.
Earlier, as wrote rus.err.ee, the prosecutor’s office presented Semilarsky suspicions of receiving a bribe and violation of anti-corruption legislation in conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained together with another Deputy Mayor Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
The prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against both vice mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov's case later reached a court that fully justified the policy.
The Valvo Semilarski investigation is still ongoing.
